    "25-Airliner Ditch - Search and Rescue": {
      "status": "pending",
      "content": "COA — Airliner Ditch - Search and Rescue\n\nASSIGNED ASSETS:\n  • F-15E Strike Eagle  — 100% allocation\n\nCOMMANDER REASONING:\nMEMORANDUM FOR RECORD\n\nDATE: 14 Oct 2034\nSUBJECT: Posture Adjustment in Response to Typhoon Francisco / Accelerated Evacuation Operations\n\n1. SITUATION: At Tick 10, the Intel Cell received updated meteorological models regarding Typhoon Francisco. Previous speed estimates were incorrect, and the storm is now forecast to make landfall at Okinawa Not Earlier Than (NET) 2200Z on 14 Oct. Higher headquarters has directed an immediate acceleration of all current operational plans.\n\n2. OPERATIONAL IMPACT: The accelerated landfall threatens our northern divert airfields and may restrict our operational airspace sooner than anticipated. Furthermore, any U.S. or allied assets stationed near Okinawa (such as Kadena AB) will likely be sheltering in place or evacuating, meaning we will lose regional support and Search and Rescue (SAR) coverage in that sector.\n\n3. DIRECTED ACTIONS (COA):\nTo comply with the directive to accelerate plans, the following actions are ordered immediately:\n\n\nLogistics / Air Mobility: All grounded C-17 Globemaster and C-130 Hercules transport aircraft at U-Tapao AB are to be prepped for immediate launch. We are compressing the refugee evacuation timeline.\n\n\nAirfield Management: The U-Tapao Runway MOG (Maximum On Ground) of 33 must be strictly monitored. With accelerated transport sorties, we cannot afford a tarmac bottleneck.\n\n\nISR Retasking: The P-8 Poseidon operating out of Cesar Basa AB is placed on standby to shift its patrol radius to monitor the southern edge of the typhoon's impact zone and track any civilian vessels caught in the accelerated weather front.\n\n4. POINT OF CONTACT: For questions regarding this MFR, coordinate directly with the JOC Operations Cell Lead.",
